{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585934"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:22:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:22:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15037"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15037"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7725"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67192"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7725"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15037"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52648"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18867"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18869"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67192"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA kidney biopsy specimen shows dilated tubules filled with pink-staining material. The microscopic appearance resembles thyroid tissue, with surrounding interstitial inflammation and fibrosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this histological appearance?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thyroidisation","Follicularisation","Tubularisation","Colloidisation","Glomerulisation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe characteristic appearance described is called \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroidisation\u003C/strong\u003E, where dilated renal tubules become filled with eosinophilic (pink-staining) material, creating a pattern that resembles thyroid follicles. This occurs in chronic pyelonephritis due to ongoing inflammation causing tubular damage and atrophy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFollicularisation\u003C/strong\u003E is not a recognised pathological term in renal pathology\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETubularisation\u003C/strong\u003E is not the correct term for this distinctive appearance\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColloidisation\u003C/strong\u003E while suggestive of thyroid-like appearance, is not the accepted term for this pattern\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlomerulisation\u003C/strong\u003E refers to changes in blood vessels, not tubular changes\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe thyroidisation pattern is accompanied by other features of chronic pyelonephritis including interstitial inflammation, fibrosis, and tubular atrophy. The pink-staining material within the dilated tubules represents accumulated protein-rich fluid.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Thyroidisation is the histological appearance of dilated tubules filled with eosinophilic material in chronic pyelonephritis, resembling thyroid follicles.","Chronic pyelonephritis leads to characteristic morphological changes including interstitial inflammation and tubular atrophy.","The thyroidisation pattern is caused by accumulation of protein-rich material within damaged and dilated renal tubules."],"references":["Ito S, Kobayashi A, Tsuchiya T, Moriyama Y, Kikuchi M, Deguchi T, Yamaguchi Y. Thyroidization in renal allografts. Clin Transplant. 2009 Aug;23 Suppl 20:6-9. doi: 10.1111/j.1399-0012.2009.01001.x. PMID: 19594588.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52648"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15037"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52648"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-03T22:57:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T22:58:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7725"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67192"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags",